    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-05-17T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-05-17T16:00:00-05:00" n="353"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d353">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">683.84A/5–1751: Circular telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in Iraq</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d353fn1">Telegram drafted by Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BJR1"
                            >Barrow</persName> and approved for transmission by Mr. <persName
                            corresp="#p_JOT1">Jones</persName>. Clearance obtained from Mr.
                            <persName corresp="#p_LJW1">Ludlow</persName> for <gloss
                            target="#t_UNP1">UNP</gloss> and Mr. <persName corresp="#p_RFG1"
                            >Ranney</persName> for <gloss target="#t_BNA1">BNA</gloss>. Repeated
                        priority to Damascus. Repeated also on routine basis to Amman, Beirut,
                        Cairo, Jerusalem, Jidda, London, New York, Paris, and Tel Aviv.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-05-17T17:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 17, 1951—5 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>713. While not disputing defensive character Iraqi action in transferring air
                    units Syria, Dept considers it unfortunate action taken while Syria–Israel
                    dispute <hi rend="italic">sub judice</hi> in <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss>.
                    Action, which hardly necessary in view acceptance by Syria and Israel of <gloss
                        target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> cease-fire resolution of May 9 [<hi rend="italic"
                        >8</hi>], lends itself to propaganda claims of Arab “aggressive intent” and
                    has already created adverse reaction in US.</p>
                <p>Inform <gloss target="#t_FonOff1">FonOff</gloss> of foregoing emphasizing that it
                    is to interests of Syria<note n="2" xml:id="d353fn2">In telegram 645 from
                        Damascus, May 20, Minister <persName corresp="#p_CCW1">Cannon</persName> in
                        part indicated that he had discussed the matter with Prime Minister Qudsi.
                        He concluded: “From US viewpoint I wonder if we have much to gain at this
                        stage by pressing further representations. It seems to us what good will we
                        may have accumulated might best be used to bring Arab states round to
                        reasonable settlement of various problems connected with present dispute and
                        requiring Arab concessions.” (683.84A/5–2051)</note> and Arabs generally to
                    refrain from precipitate action prejudicing dispassionate consideration of
                    Syria-Israel dispute in <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss>. Missions in other
                    Arab caps requested to speak to govts to which accredited similarly. London
                    discuss with <gloss target="#t_FonOff1">FonOff</gloss> and report UK
                    reaction.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_ADG1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
